const_ring_hom_eq_algebra_map:
-- One could also build a `Π i, R i`-algebra structure on `Π i, A i`,
-- when each `A i` is an `R i`-algebra, although I'm not sure that it's useful.
/-- When `R` is commutative and permits an `algebra_map`, `pi.const_ring_hom` is equal to that
map. -/
@[simp]
theorem const_ring_hom_eq_algebra_map : constRingHom A R = algebra_map R (A → R) :=
  rfl
#align const_ring_hom_eq_algebra_map const_ring_hom_eq_algebra_map
const_alg_hom_eq_algebra_of_id:
@[simp]
theorem const_alg_hom_eq_algebra_of_id : const_alg_hom R A R = algebra.of_id R (A → R) :=
  rfl
#align const_alg_hom_eq_algebra_of_id const_alg_hom_eq_algebra_of_id

-- The indexing type
-- The scalar type
-- The family of types already equipped with instances
theorem algebra_map_def {r : CommSemiring R} [s : ∀ i, Semiring (f i)] [∀ i, algebra R (f i)] (a : R) :
    algebra_map R (∀ i, f i) a = fun i => algebra_map R (f i) a :=
  rfl
#align algebra_map_def algebra_map_def
algebra_map_apply:
@[simp]
theorem algebra_map_apply {r : CommSemiring R} [s : ∀ i, Semiring (f i)] [∀ i, algebra R (f i)] (a : R) (i : I) :
    algebra_map R (∀ i, f i) a i = algebra_map R (f i) a :=
  rfl
#align algebra_map_apply algebra_map_apply
